E. COLI EHEC - USA (24): (OHIO), O157, PICNIC
*********************************************
A ProMED-mail post
http://www.promedmail.org
ProMED-mail is a program of the
International Society for Infectious Diseases
http://www.isid.org

Date: Mon 23 Jul 2012
Source: Public Health - Dayton & Montgomery County (OH) [edited]
http://www.phdmc.org/article/update_on_e._coli_0157_outbreak_in_germantown2


As a result of eating food at a picnic at Neff's Lawn Care in Germantown, OH, at least 75 individuals have become ill. Of those, 14 have been hospitalized. Public Health - Dayton & Montgomery County is continuing an investigation into the cause of the foodborne outbreak. Estimates are that as many as 300 people may have attended an annual customer appreciation picnic held by Neff's Lawn Care on 3 Jul 2012. Of the ill, 18 have been confirmed as being infected by _E. coli_ O157. Three individuals are experiencing hemolytic uremic syndrome (HUS), a disease that destroys red blood cells and can cause acute kidney failure. Those affected include a 4-year-old female, a 14-year-old male, and a 73-year-old male. All 3 are in serious medical condition.

Two secondary cases of _E. coli_ O157 have been reported, which emphasize the importance of hand washing to prevent the spread of the organism within the family unit.

Public Health is continuing to gather information. Investigators are also looking at food sources, food handling and storage practices, food temperature controls, and the potential of cross contamination of the food.

--
Communicated by:
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>

[In the week since the last posting of this outbreak, 7 more cases have come to light, of which only one is a secondary case. It is likely that most, if not all, of the primary cases do not have more recent dates of onset but are just now being reported. ProMED awaits any information regarding the potential food vehicle. - Mod.LL

A HealthMap/ProMED-mail map can be accessed at: http://healthmap.org/r/1BY2.]
